[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] In software design, **inversion of control** (**IoC**) is a design principle in which custom-written portions of a computer program receive the flow of control from an external source (e.g. a framework).
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] The term "inversion" is historical: a software architecture with this design "inverts" control as compared to procedural programming.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] In procedural programming, a program's custom code calls reusable libraries to take care of generic tasks, but with inversion of control, it is the external code or framework that is in control and calls the custom code.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Inversion of control has been widely used by application development frameworks since the rise of GUI environments and continues to be used both in GUI environments and in web server application frameworks.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Inversion of control makes the framework extensible by the methods defined by the application programmer.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Event-driven programming is often implemented using IoC so that the custom code need only be concerned with the handling of events, while the event loop and dispatch of events/messages is handled by the framework or the runtime environment.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] In web server application frameworks, dispatch is usually called routing, and handlers may be called endpoints.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] The phrase "inversion of control" has separately also come to be used in the community of Java programmers to refer specifically to the patterns of dependency injection (passing services to objects that need them) that occur with "IoC containers" in Java frameworks such as the Spring Framework.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] As an example, with traditional programming, the main function of an application might make function calls into a menu library to display a list of available commands and query the user to select one.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] The library thus would return the chosen option as the value of the function call, and the main function uses this value to execute the associated command.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] This style was common in text-based interfaces.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] For example, an email client may show a screen with commands to load new mail, answer the current mail, create new mail, etc., and the program execution would block until the user presses a key to select a command.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] With inversion of control, on the other hand, the program would be written using a software framework that knows common behavioral and graphical elements, such as windowing systems, menus, controlling the mouse, and toolbars.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] The custom code "fills in the blanks" for the framework, such as supplying a table of menu items and registering a code subroutine for each item, but it is the framework that monitors the user's actions and invokes the subroutine when a menu item is selected.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] In the mail client example, the framework could follow both the keyboard and mouse inputs and call the command invoked by the user by either means and at the same time monitor the network interface to find out if new messages arrive and refresh the screen when some network activity is detected.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] The same framework could be used as the skeleton for a spreadsheet program or a text editor.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Conversely, the framework knows nothing about Web browsers, spreadsheets, or text editors; implementing their functionality takes custom code.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Inversion of control carries the strong connotation that the reusable code and the problem-specific code are developed independently even though they operate together in an application.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Callbacks, schedulers, event loops, and the template method are examples of design patterns that follow the inversion of control principle, although the term is most commonly used in the context of object-oriented programming.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Inversion of control is sometimes referred to as the "Hollywood Principle: Don't call us, we'll call you," reflecting how frameworks dictate execution flow.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] The etymology of the phrase has been traced back to 1988, but it is closely related to the concept of **program inversion** described by Michael Jackson in his Jackson Structured Programming methodology in the 1970s.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] A bottom-up parser can be seen as an inversion of a top-down parser: in the one case, the control lies with the parser, while in the other case, it lies with the receiving application.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] The phrase was further popularized in 2004 by Robert C.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Martin and Martin Fowler, the latter of whom traces the term's origins to the 1980s.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] In traditional programming, the flow of the business logic is determined by objects that are statically bound to one another.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] With inversion of control, the flow depends on the object graph that is built up during program execution.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Such a dynamic flow is made possible by object interactions that are defined through abstractions.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] This run-time binding is achieved by mechanisms such as dependency injection or a service locator.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] In IoC, the code could also be linked statically during compilation, but finding the code to execute by reading its description from external configuration instead of with a direct reference in the code itself.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] In dependency injection, a dependent object or module is coupled to the object it needs at run time.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Which particular object will satisfy the dependency during program execution typically cannot be known at compile time using static analysis.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] While described in terms of object interaction here, the principle can apply to other programming methodologies besides object-oriented programming.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] In order for the running program to bind objects to one another, the objects must possess compatible interfaces.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] For example, class `A` may delegate behavior to interface `I` which is implemented by class `B`; the program instantiates `A` and `B`, and then injects `B` into `A`.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] Web browsers implement inversion of control for DOM events in HTML.
[src:dependency-injection-web/inversion-of-control] The application developer uses `document.addEventListener()` to register a callback.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] In software engineering, a **microservice** architecture is an architectural pattern that organizes an application into a collection of loosely coupled, fine-grained services that communicate through lightweight protocols.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] This pattern allows teams to develop, deploy, and scale services independently, improving modularity, scalability, and adaptability.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] However, it introduces additional complexity, particularly in managing distributed systems and inter-service communication, making the initial implementation more challenging compared to a monolithic architecture.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] There is no single, universally agreed-upon definition of microservices.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] However, they are generally characterized by a focus on modularity, with each service designed around a specific business capability.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] These services are loosely coupled, independently deployable, and often developed and scaled separately, enabling greater flexibility and agility in managing complex systems.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Microservices architecture is closely associated with principles such as domain-driven design, decentralization of data and governance, and the flexibility to use different technologies for individual services to best meet their requirements.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] It is common for microservices architectures to be adopted for cloud-native applications, serverless computing, and applications using lightweight container deployment via OS-level virtualization.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] According to Fowler, because of the large number (when compared to monolithic application implementations) of services, decentralized continuous delivery and DevOps with holistic service monitoring are necessary to effectively develop, maintain, and operate such applications.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] A consequence of (and rationale for) following this approach is that the individual microservices can be individually scaled.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] In the monolithic approach, an application supporting three functions would have to be scaled in its entirety even if only one of these functions had a resource constraint.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] With microservices, only the microservice supporting the function with resource constraints needs to be scaled out, thus providing resource and cost optimization benefits.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Despite its benefits, microservices architecture introduces challenges such as increased operational complexity, network latency, and the need for robust monitoring and fault tolerance mechanisms.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing design in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Each cell operates independently, handling a subset of requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] A cell typically consists of multiple microservices and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] In some implementations, entire sets of microservices are replicated across multiple cells, enabling requests to be rerouted to another operational cell if one experiences a failure.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] This approach is intended to improve system-wide resilience by limiting the impact of localized failures.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Some implementations incorporate circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to mitigate cascading failures among microservices, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in certain large-scale distributed systems where fault isolation and redundancy are design priorities.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Its implementation varies based on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and specific operational goals.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] In 1999, software developer Peter Rodgers had been working on the Dexter research project at Hewlett Packard Labs, whose aim was to make code less brittle and to make large-scale, complex software systems robust to change.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] Ultimately this path of research led to the development of resource-oriented computing (ROC), a generalized computation abstraction in which REST is a special subset.
[src:dependency-injection-web/microservices] In 2005, during a presentation at the Web Services Edge conference, Rodgers argued for "REST-services" and stated that "Software components are Micro-Web-Services...
